{{About|Mian People|Mian (surname)|Mian (surname)}}

{{Infobox ethnic group
| group      = Mian
| population = 3,500<ref name="agom">{{cite book | last = Fedden | first = Olcher Sebastian | year = 2007 | title = A Grammar of Mian, a Papuan Language of New Guinea}}</ref>
| popplace   = [[Papua New Guinea]]:<br />[[Sandaun Province|Sandaun province]],<br />[[Telefomin|Telefomin district]]
| languages  = [[Mian language|Mian]], [[Tok Pisin]]
| related    = [[Bimin people|Bimin]], [[Faiwol people|Faiwol]], [[Nakai people|Nakai]], [[Setaman people|Setaman]], [[Suganga people|Suganga]], [[Tifal people|Tifal]], [[Telefol people|Telefol]], [[Urapmin people|Urapmin]]
}}

The '''Mian people''' (Mianmin) are a people living in the [[Telefomin|Telefomin district]] of the [[Sandaun Province|Sandaun province]] in [[Papua New Guinea]]. The number of Mian is 3,500, based on the number of speakers of their language, [[Mian language|Mian]].

The Mian are living in small villages in mountainous areas with rainforest and rivers; conditions which makes transport very limited, almost only restricted to walking, which however have helped them retaining their traditional way of life, based on [[hunting]] and [[agriculture]], including [[slash-and-burn]]. They grow [[sweet potato]]es, [[sago]], [[banana]]s, [[pineapple]]s, [[breadfruit]]s, [[papaya|pawpaw]], [[sugarcane]]s, [[pumpkin]]s and [[Squash (plant)|squashes]], and in more recent times, also [[Orange (fruit)|orange]]s, [[tomato]]es, [[bean]]s, [[peanut]]s and [[coconut]]s. [[Animal]]s they hunt and catch include [[pig]]s, [[cassowary|cassowaries]], [[bird]]s, [[fish]], [[snake]]s and small [[reptile]]s.<ref name="agom" /> Hunting is exclusively for men, while the women are normally the ones preparing the food.

