{{use mdy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox organization | map = | formation = 1983 | type = [[Non governmental organization]] | purpose = museum of women's history | coords = {{Coord|32.739|-117.214|display=title}} | formerly = Women's History Reclamation Project, Women's History Museum & Educational Center | name = Women's Museum of California | abbreviation = WMofC | founder = Mary Maschal | location = [[Liberty Station, San Diego]] | website = http://womensmuseumca.org/ | founding_location = [[Golden Hill, San Diego]] }} The '''Women's Museum of California''' (WMofC) is a nonprofit museum located in [[San Diego|San Diego, California]] and dedicated to [[women's history]]. It was first organized under the names the Women's History Reclamation Project and then the Women's History Museum and Educational Center. It was founded in 1983.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N6fLCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA525&dq=%22women's%20museum%20of%20california%22&pg=PA525#v=onepage&q=%22women's%20museum%20of%20california%22&f=false|title=Women in Culture: An Intersectional Anthology for Gender and Women's Studies|last=|first=|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2016|isbn=9781118541128|editor-last=Scott|editor-first=Bonnie Kime|location=|pages=525|editor-last2=Cayleff|editor-first2=Susan E.|editor-last3=Donadey|editor-first3=Anne|editor-last4=Lara|editor-first4=Irene}}</ref> In addition to exhibits and programs offered, the WMofC also co-founded and hosts the San Diego County Women's Hall of Fame. The museum is located at [[Liberty Station, San Diego|Liberty Station]] and has exhibit space, archives, a library and a store that features items made exclusively by women.<ref name=":2" /> Other museum offerings include speakers and monthly lecture series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/places/womans-history-museum-and-educational-center/|title=Women's History Museum and Educational Center|last=|first=|date=|publisher=KPBS |access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref>
== History == The museum had its roots with the [[women's rights]] activist, Mary B. Maschal who collected items from women's history in her home.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2012/sep/06/carrying-the-torch-for-womens-history/|title=Carrying the Torch for Women's History|last=Barton|first=Shawnee|date=September 6, 2012|work=the San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> The home had formally belonged to a [[Suffragette|suffragist]], Veronica Burke.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohosandiego.org/reflections/2011/suffragist.htm|title=Sleeping Porches & Suffragist Banners|last=van Neck-Yoder|first=Hilda|date=|website=Save Our Heritage Organisation|publisher=|access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> Maschal had been collecting artifacts relating to women's history since the 1970s.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20050324/news_lz1c24women.html|title=Honoring the Feats of Women in History|last=Arya|first=Hala Ali|date=March 24, 2005|work=UT San Diego|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> She finally opened her collection to the public in 1983, naming it the Women's History Reclamation Project (WHRP).<ref name=":0" /> Maschal felt a passion for collecting artifacts because of her "own disappointment over the lack of knowledge about women's history among the younger generation."<ref name=":4" /> Maschal also received a grant in 1984 in order to conduct and collect [[oral history]] interviews.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=43}}
Maschal moved her collection to the Art Union Building in [[Golden Hill, San Diego|Golden Hill]] in 1997.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.lajollalight.com/news/2015/sep/16/womens-museum-assitance-league/|title=Women's History Museum Chronicles Assistance League Story|last=Hutchison|first=Linda|date=September 16, 2015|work=La Jolla Light|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> Maschel died in 1998, and Sue Gonda took over the museum.<ref name=":3" /> In 2000, the museum sponsored a Women's History Poetry contest, which was held at the same time as an exhibit titled In Our Own Voice: women's History through Women's Poetry.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=43}} The museum co-created the San Diego County Women's Hall of Fame in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womensmuseumca.org/hall-of-fame|title=Women's Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Women's Museum of California|access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> In 2003, the project changed its name to the Women's History Museum and Educational Center (WHMEC).<ref name=":3" />
The Women's History Museum and Educational Center changed its name again, this time to the Women's Museum of California (WMofC) in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/jan/04/womens-history-museum-announces-name-change/|title=Women's History Museum Announces Name Change|last=Cadelago|first=Christopher|date=January 4, 2011|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> They concurrently updated the museum [[logo]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://sdcitybeat.com/blog-15107-san-diego-women's-museum-moves-to-ntc.html|title=A San Diego Museum Moves to NTC and Changes its Name|last=Morlan|first=Kinsee|date=January 3, 2011|work=San Diego City Beat|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> WMC also moved to the [[Liberty Station, San Diego|Liberty Station]] Promenade in [[Point Loma, San Diego|Point Loma]] in 2012.<ref name=":0" /> The new location was three times larger than their former location at Golden Hill.<ref name=":1" />
== Helen Hawkins Memorial Library and Research Archive == Part of the museum is a [[library]] and [[archive]]. The Helen Hawkins Memorial Library and Research Archive includes books and several special collections.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=43}} Part of the special collections is the Alice Park Archive which collects artifacts from the [[women's suffrage]] movement from the late 19th century and early 20th century.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=43}} The special collections also include papers documenting the career of [[Lucy Killea]], a collection of materials relating to the UN Conference on the Status of Women and the Neff-LeClair Collection of period women's clothing dating from the 18th century on.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=43}}
== San Diego County Women's Hall of Fame == The Hall of Fame was created in 2001, partly through the WMofC and other organizations.<ref name=":3" /> Some organizations that have partnered with WMofC for the hall of fame include the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]], [[MANA, A National Latina Organization]] and [[Executive Women International]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ward |first=Denise T. |date=January 14, 2002 |title=Nominations Sought for San Diego Women's Hall of Fame |url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=6092739&site=ehost-live |newspaper=San Diego Business Journal |volume=23 |issue=2 |page=32 |accessdate=July 12, 2016 |subscription=yes |via=EBSCO}}</ref> In other years, other groups, such as the Commission on the Status of Women, San Diego State University's department of Women's Studies and the Women's Center of the University of California, San Diego have participated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2014/mar/29/tp-women-honored-for-inspirational-contributions/|title=Women Honored for Inspirational Contributions|last=Rocha|first=Michael James|date=March 29, 2014|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=July 12, 2016|via=}}</ref> Inductions into the hall of fame take place during [[Women's History Month]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/mar/11/womens-museum-features-diverse-collection/|title=Women's Museum Features Diverse Collection|last=Gonzalez|first=Blanca|date=March 11, 2011|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=July 11, 2016|via=}}</ref> Each year about five women are inducted.{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=45}}
The San Diego County Women's Hall of Fame mission is "to acknowledge and honor women who have significantly contributed to the quality of life and who have made outstanding volunteer contributions in San Diego County."{{Sfn|Russo|2008|p=45}}
